  "notes": [
    "All transfer applicants must meet the University of California admissions eligibility requirements and the campus’s admission selection criteria. All requirements must be completed by the end of the spring term prior to transfer. For more information on UC admissions eligibility and admission to UC Santa Cruz, visit the Admissions website . The UC Santa Cruz Transfer Admission Guarantee (TAG) is a formal agreement that guarantees your fall admission to your chosen major, provided you are transferring from a California Community College and meet specific requirements. Visit the UC Santa Cruz TAG webpage for more information.",
    "Some Advanced Placement (AP), International Baccalaureate Higher Level (IBH), and Advanced Level (A-level) exams satisfy UCSC course requirements. UCSC's exam credit policies may be found on the Degree Progress Unit website .",
    "This is a non-screening major: completion of specific major coursework is not required for admission. However, students are strongly encouraged to complete as many lower-division courses as possible from the \" Recommended Preparation \" section below to support timely degree completion. Students applying to non-screening majors are also encouraged to complete the California General Education Transfer Curriculum (Cal-GETC) or all UC Santa Cruz general education requirements prior to transfer. For guidance on incorporating Cal-GETC into your academic plan, consult your community college counselor.",
    "PREPARATION FOR THE MAJOR Transfer students are strongly advised to complete two years of language study at accredited two and four year institutions. While two years of prior language study is strongly advised, transfer students should be able to complete the applied linguistics and multilingualism major in normative time as long as they place into language Level 4 (Level 5 for students entering UC Santa Cruz in the winter term) upon arrival at UC Santa Cruz. ﻿Effective the 2025–2026 academic year, UCSC no longer offers German or Portuguese language courses. Because this major requires intermediate-high proficiency in a non-English language (equivalent to two years of UCSC coursework), students who began these languages at their community college will be unable to continue them at UCSC. Although not required for admission, transfer students are also encouraged to complete the following courses, or their articulated equivalents, prior to transferring: LING 50: Introduction to Linguistics APLX 80: Introduction to Applied Linguistics Students are also encouraged to complete the California General Education Transfer Curriculum (Cal-GETC) or all UC Santa Cruz general education requirements before transferring. For guidance on incorporating Cal-GETC into your academic plan, consult your community college counselor. Please visit the Languages and Applied Linguistics website to learn more about this major. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Applied Linguistics and Multilingualism B.A. Program Statement"
